annotations:
Fell asleep by the phone
 I missed a message or two
 Deleted them ‘cause they weren’t you

This is referencing the part in The Great Gatsby when Gatsby was waiting for Daisy to call him and leave New York with him, after the incident in the car. Gatsby stayed up till 4 im the morning, but she never called.

I miss the weight of your words
 I miss the bruises they left

Daisy missed Gatsby and waited for him till she met Tom, but when she was finally reunited with Gatsby she fell into the middle of Tom and Gatsby’s feud. She missed all the things Gatsby said he would do for her.
Babe

babe, a term of endearment, yet one with a more one sided meaning in this use as it’s said without true ownership of the term (or a true requited relationship). also this story is, like this love, very one sided, thus there can be no direct conversational response echoing the same sentiments unless the song is more of a dduet of some kind (10/10 would want to hear a lil duet featuring another girl (bi tings 🤪) or @tuckerrivera or @youngfriend…..
I broke my knuckles in a fight, you were crying in the back of the room

I took this back to Tom Buchanan and how he punched Myrtle in the face when they are in the apartment in chapter 2. If Daisy was there she would be quietly weeping in the corner until she got angry enough to set “the world on fire”
Shape of your voice
Daisy’s voice is described often in the book, as said in an earlier annotation. Her voice had shape and weight in the world of Gatsby.
You smiled was a promise
Nick mentions the power of gatsby’s smile more than once in the book. it could also be a reference to Daisy, whose looks were a source of admiration from all
I waited up for your call
personally, I can see this from Myrtle’s point of view as she was always calling Tom at dinnertime, waiting for him to pick up
I wrecked my house a hundred times just to see you walk into a room

okay lol for some reason every time i sing this line i literally can’t stop thinking about this one episode of how i met your mother HAHAHA

for those of you who haven’t seen the show, ted is a dorky, hopeless romantic type, and in this one particular episode he throws like two weekends of parties all in hopes of this one girl coming. i don’t actually remember how the episode pans out but i thiiiiink she doesn’t even come? either way, he’s stuck with annoyed roommates and a hangover, and nothing went the way he wanted it to.

but tbh in hindsight, whether you are jay gatsby or ted mosby, please do not throw a million parties like this for someone instead of just hanging out with them. i am telling you now they will most likely think it is alarming behavior. not a cute look. psa is over

also love himym but fuck ted mosby homie can shut it

And then you’re crashing my car
 And now I’m taking the blame
i could go into this but then i’m realllly spoiling the entire novel so i’ll leave it up to you to analyze lol

And they can dance to the songs
 And they can drink all the wine
 Because the high might be theirs
 But all the bottles were mine

this is probably my favorite set of lyrics in the whole song – i think it captures the overall theme in a really succinct but important way.

i think it’s easy to pretend that just because you once “had” someone, they’re still partly in your “possession” even after they’ve moved on. obviously this is a really toxic way to view things, but it’s also kind of natural human behavior; a sort of manifestation of jealousy, hidden in denial.

description.plain: Written when she was 16 and finished at 19, “bored&blind” for ella jane is a true manifestation of evolution, both personally and musically. Though the artist penned the lyrics in a haze of sophomore year frustration, trying hard to capture the true pain and excitement of an unrequited crush, the finished song reflects a new level of maturity and hindsight that her 16 year-old self couldn’t yet see. The hooky, pop-driven melody and upbeat tempo work to capture the song’s inherent youthfulness, but it is truly the production, with percussive guitar plucks and a tasteful blend of live and electronic sound palettes, that catapults “bored&blind” into the indie world.

annotations: ‘Cause right now, it’s sittin’ in your basement
Her heart is sitting in his basement. As things left in the basement are often in storage and not being used, it refers to her having a crush on him without him reciprocating it/knowing about it.

And when I’m lookin’ at you
 Everything disappears
 And lovin’ gets a little bit lonelier

Ella states that she’s so mesmerised by this person that when she is looking at them, the rest of the world disappears.
 As stated in the comments, “lovin gets a little bit lonelier” refers to the one sided nature of the attraction, Ella being left lonely by the person she likes due to him not noticing her.

’Cause I locked myself inside his coffin
 And I was dumb enough
 To throw away the—

This lyric is likely referring to ella’s unrequited love- locking herself inside his coffin refers to having a crush on him, and throwing away the key symbolises not being able to end the crush or “escape” the “coffin”.

Hidden in the back with some stolen art
 And, hey, Mona Lisa
The Mona Lisa itself was stolen in 1911. It also owes much of its fame to its theft.

But I would rather watch you from miles away
 Than be a little closer and bored and blind
The artist is saying they would rather keep their distance because they are scared to talk to the person that has their heart. They don’t want to embarrass  themself.

Well, how many figures will it take
 For you to bring me back my heart?

This line feels like Ella was trying to say that her crush had her heart without even realizing it. She wants to move on, take her heart back, and eventually give it to someone else. She wants them to discover they have her heart without embarrassing herself.

description.plain: A calling card is something that a person leaves behind at a particular place, usually at the scene of a murder, that identifies them. In this song’s version of a calling card, the murder is used as an analogy for relationships, particularly falling in love and then being dumped. ella jane knows that it is incredibly likely that this man will try to “murder” her, aka making her fall in love and leaving, and wants to stop it, but instead she is addicted to the man.

body.plain: A calling card is something that a person leaves behind at a particular place, usually at the scene of a murder, that identifies them. In this song’s version of a calling card, the murder is used as an analogy for relationships, particularly falling in love and then being dumped. ella jane knows that it is incredibly likely that this man will try to “murder” her, aka making her fall in love and leaving, and wants to stop it, but instead she is addicted to the man.

annotations: Pulling at the fray till it comes undone

Frayed fabric is easy to pull, the entire fabric will come apart with a pull. She’s using the fray as a metaphor for evidence of his wrongdoing. She’s saying she could find all his evidence that he’s cheating until she’s torn apart his entire scheme.
Whisper with a voice that I can’t outrun
Even if she figures out what his “calling card” or his tell or move is, she will never be able to escape his closeness, his whisper. She won’t be able to escape being hurt by him.

Where you go, I follow
 So you lead me to the murder scene
 And I knew you’re sharpening your
 I knew you’re sharpening your

She’s saying she’ll be next to him, by his side, even when he comes clean and tells her he’s seeing other people. Sharpening his knife refers to the last pre-chorus which translates into the singer understanding that he’ll never change, he’ll still be that way even after he tells her. Sharpening his knife to hurt and hurt over and over.

I got a problem
 I’m hooked on you like nicotine
 I couldn’t quit you if I tried

But the singer has a problem. She’s seeing all this negative evidence of this guy doing terrible things but she’s hooked on him. She’s in his “jean pocket”. She’d addicted to seeing him, spending time with him. She wouldn’t be able to save herself from his wrongdoing.

I heard a scream from down the block
 Bloodstains in places where they shouldn’t be

The “scream” could be referring to her hearing rumors about other girls hearts getting broken by this guy. “Bloodstains” being her noticing evidence of these girls around this guy. She’s hearing rumors and she’s seeing evidence of his wrong-doings.
You shaved your head and got a fake ID

He’s covering his tracks, this is a metaphor too. The singer is saying that he is lying, covering up what he’s doing wrong, which is most likely cheating or talking to other girls. In reference to the fake ID line, he’s maybe pretending to be other people/using a different name.
Sophie said to call the cops
I’d argue this is a metaphor too. Sophie calling the cops could mean that a friend of the singer is telling her to tell on him, find out if what he’s doing is wrong.

Got me in your jean pocket
 Something’s telling me I’m not the only one
She’s saying she knows she’s under his control, that he is keeping her around and she’s not going anywhere. But she thinks she’s not the only one he’s keeping on the line.
What’s your calling card, killer?
Singer is asking what his tell is. What’s his move? How will she know when she’s been tricked/hurt?

So I’ll let you over
 But I’ll stand right by the fire escape
 Cause I bet you’re sharpening your knife
She’s keeping him around but now she’s wary. She’s ready to get away from him at any moment, even though she still has him in her life. She has a feeling he’s ready to hurt her.

annotations:
Just give me a minute
 So I can drink up the feeling we had just one last time

this is a very relatable line that i feel like a lot of girl can relate to. letting something or someone you love go can be so hard, and sometimes you just need to stop in the moment and take a second to feel it before you let it go.

...When the silence gets too loud
 I’ll feel you calling me home

when i started writing The City, i knew i wanted to end the song on a sort of unsettling note, with these specific lyrics and a repeated, isolated vocal. after a round that takes up over a minute of the song (in which i essentially say that i am finally content outside of this “city”), this statement about missing that “city” is a glaring contrast.

(Ah-ey-ey-ey, ah-ey-ey-ey)
 (Ah-ey-ey-ey, ah-ey-ey-ey)
my deepest lyrics yet, i think

There’s nothing left for me
 In this city anymore

this was a phrase i had been coming back to a lot – i think i heard something like it on some show i was watching? i found it so dramatic originally, that statement of “tHERe’S nOThiNg hEre fOR mE aNyMoRE”, but it eventually really struck me.

i think that phrase was sitting in the notes section on my phone for about a year until i suddenly got this idea for a metaphor that compares a lived-in, breaking-down apartment to that strange feeling of growing apart from people you love. once i drew that connection, i felt like i had come to a huge moment of clarity (both personally and lyrically), and it all started coming together :))

description.plain: “AUGUST IS A FEVER” is, in short, a full-fledged identity crisis unfolding in real time to the upbeat tempo of an indie-pop anthem. Written the summer before ella’s senior year of high school, it captures what it’s like to be seventeen and uncertain, articulating the sheer oxymoron of finding both fear and comfort in familiarity.

body.plain: “AUGUST IS A FEVER” is, in short, a full-fledged identity crisis unfolding in real time to the upbeat tempo of an indie-pop anthem. Written the summer before ella’s senior year of high school, it captures what it’s like to be seventeen and uncertain, articulating the sheer oxymoron of finding both fear and comfort in familiarity.

annotations:
Thinking if I run away I’ll change my name
 To one that feels like mine

this lyric means that she will almost alter her identity to fit one that she believes is meant to be hers. she has lived seventeen years without having the freedom to do so, and if she were to run away and leave her old life behind – she would completely restart and pick a new name that she feels should have been hers all along. she has spent so many years living in who she is expected to be and this fake persona that if she was to run away she would start afresh and leave all traces of her old life behind.

August is a fever
 ’Cause we’re too hot and cold and homesick all the time

Fevers are typically caused by a physical sickness, but here it is being used as a symptom of homesickness, a different type of illness that the person is experiencing.

The description of it being both too hot and too cold represents the ever-changing feelings about the situation, oscillating between the sensation of fear and comfort that the song portrays.
So I’ll pack my things and leave myself behind

hey! to me at least this kinda means that liberating perfection of feeling so entirely in the moment that even your own personality doesn’t hold you back?? often I feel restrained to upholding some sort of constant in character (especially around different people) so the idea of letting that internal pressure off for a bit and leaving yourself for me would be some kinda complete content :)
love u ella!!<3

The party’s burning down the house
 We’re drowning in your parents’ pool
 I think you’re tryna smoke me out
 Who let me think you’re so cool? And
 The party’s burning down the house
 We’re drowning in your parents’ pool
 I think you’re tryna smoke me out
 Who let me think you’re so fuckin’ cool?

as i got older i started to realize that the people i wanted to be like, the people i thought were “cool,” were just generally shitty people. i think that realization was a huge part of figuring out my own identity  - understanding not only who i was, but who i didn’t want to be and why. that’s what this bridge is.

I don’t wanna leave ya
 So I’ll pack my things and leave myself behind
there’s obviously no reality where i could leave one version of myself at home and send another version off into the world to explore, but writing this song let me explore that possibility.

And you like to say that you got it figured out
 But I don’t know
 No, I don’t know
 Where the hell I’m gonna go

even though at this point in the song i’d grown a lot as a person and found more comfort in where i was than when i wrote the first half, this second pre-chorus really emphasizes the fact that i still had no idea what the i actually wanted to do with my life. i was happier, but just as lost.

And you like to say that you got it figured out
 But I don’t know
 No, I don’t know
 Where the hell I’m gonna go
 And I’m aware
 That you found a place to hide
 But I don’t know
 No, I don’t know
 How to make it out alive

i spent my entire adolescence in glaring denial of the fact that i really just wanted to write songs all day, every day, for the rest of my life. my school was pretty competitive and there wasn’t a ton of emphasis on creativity, so i truly didn’t know that a career in music was even a possibility. even if the rational part of my brain knew that most people my age didn’t have any clue what their futures would look like, they were really good at making it seem like they did, and that scared the shit out of me. it still kind of does.

these lines aren’t solely about the uncertainty of my future – they’re also about my identity in general. i was really anxious and spent a lot of middle school and early high school feeling like everyone was judging me (even if they weren’t), which made trying to figure out who i was as a person really difficult. i was in my head all the time and couldn’t get out, and when you walk around like that you’re obviously going to struggle with gaining any realistic perspective on the people around you. that’s kind of the mindset i was in when i started writing this pre-chorus – when i finished the song though, i was in a bit of a better place.

I’m sitting in the parking lot
 For the second time today

small town summers babyyyy

my friends and i would literally just drive from parking lot to parking lot every day after work, and that was our daily routine bc there was nothing else to do. what’s so funny about it to me is that this really only makes sense to other people who grew up in small-town, suburban america. it’s this shared cultural phenomenon of being 17 and really fucking bored.

Poison spilling down my throat
 But New York’s underwater in a week

this line makes me laugh because it’s just like. very gen z lol

i feel like people my age are so nihilistic in our humor/general approach to life, because how else can we really deal with all the bullshit in the world that we were kinda just handed? i.e., does it really matter if drinking is bad for my mental/physical state and is killing me if global warming’s probably gonna get to me first anyway?

We wait until the moon gets high then cross that line
 Electric while we can
 You like to fill your lungs with smoke
 I feel like I’m just stuck between your teeth

something that made me fall in love with songwriting was realizing that it never really has to be within certain parameters or time limits (at least in my own creative process). i have really bad ADD and i’m also a huge perfectionist, which is normally a lethal combination when it comes to time constraints – but with songwriting i’ve learned to really see the value in taking my time. it’s the one time being a generally ~slow~ person works to my advantage lol .

because of that, i think, my songs have become these really unique time capsules in my life – a monument of a singular moment, or reflective of whole period of time during which i grew or my perspective changed. and for august, it was definitely the latter.

this verse is about my changing relationship with weed/alcohol throughout high school (lol). when i was younger it was a big source of my anxiety – i was always TERRIFIED of being perceived as too young or innocent, and i felt really judged by the people around me if i didn’t want to partake. as i got older and learned to surround myself with people who genuinely cared about me and didn’t judge me, i started to enjoy going out and drinking. it was actually really interesting to finish writing this verse from such a different mental place than when i started it – i didn’t realize just how much drugs/alcohol symbolized fear and judgement for me until i had been able to get past that and find some sort of confidence within myself.

looking back, i think it was also really weird to be experiencing my first true moments of escapism at a time in my life where i just felt really bored and trapped and unsure of myself. on the one hand i really did love the security and comfort of familiarity, but i couldn’t help but wonder how my view of sobriety might differ had i grown up in a busier environment.
